129
00:07:55.312 --> 00:07:57.832
So one useful framework is the ecosocial

130
00:07:58.792 --> 00:08:02.632
theory and many other theories that are similar.

131
00:08:03.332 --> 00:08:05.712
The central idea is that

132
00:08:06.592 --> 00:08:10.552
our bodies biologically incorporate the physical and social world

133
00:08:11.072 --> 00:08:14.972
across the life course. So embodiment, it really just

134
00:08:14.992 --> 00:08:18.772
considers the fact that our human bodies biologically

135
00:08:18.852 --> 00:08:20.312
incorporate all of the external

136
00:08:21.392 --> 00:08:25.312
stressors that we encounter. So biology is not

137
00:08:25.372 --> 00:08:26.392
separate from

138
00:08:27.612 --> 00:08:28.272
the social

139
00:08:29.732 --> 00:08:33.312
constructs. It's not separate from the physical and social

140
00:08:33.913 --> 00:08:37.432
world. It's not separate from policies, institutions,

141
00:08:37.872 --> 00:08:39.992
neighborhoods, and lived environments.

142
00:08:40.332 --> 00:08:43.172
So all of these can shape, for example, stress

143
00:08:43.632 --> 00:08:47.602
physiology, inflammation, immune processes, and other

144
00:08:47.632 --> 00:08:48.761
downstream pathways.

145
00:08:50.372 --> 00:08:53.992
This framework also reminds us that these pathways operate

146
00:08:54.002 --> 00:08:56.802
across multiple levels. So looking at this

147
00:08:57.692 --> 00:09:01.342
one example, which comes from the ACHIEVE study that's led by

148
00:09:01.372 --> 00:09:05.032
myself and Dr. Jennifer Shui, we're actually looking at

149
00:09:05.972 --> 00:09:09.481
the relationship of macro-level, meso-level, and micro-level

150
00:09:09.772 --> 00:09:13.132
