151
00:09:14.092 --> 00:09:17.392
treatment, and how all of these multi-level

152
00:09:17.472 --> 00:09:20.972
relationships drive outcomes in cervical cancer and

153
00:09:20.992 --> 00:09:22.612
disparities in these outcomes.

154
00:09:24.012 --> 00:09:27.632
So this framework and similar ecosocial

155
00:09:27.712 --> 00:09:31.312
frameworks remind us that the pathways operate across multiple levels,

156
00:09:31.952 --> 00:09:35.352
from the macro-level systems and institutions to

157
00:09:35.412 --> 00:09:39.322
neighborhoods and communities, all the way down to households and

158
00:09:39.372 --> 00:09:43.231
individuals, and also cellular processes.

159
00:09:43.242 --> 00:09:45.532
And importantly, this ecosocial thinking

160
00:09:46.852 --> 00:09:50.732
asks us to take accountability into consideration.

161
00:09:50.812 --> 00:09:54.252
So who benefits, who's harmed, and through what

162
00:09:54.272 --> 00:09:58.082
systems? So the key message is that social structure is not

163
00:09:58.132 --> 00:09:59.172
outside biology.

164
00:10:00.152 --> 00:10:01.552
It helps produce biology.

