00:50:27.408 --> 00:50:30.928
cohorts that include information on demographics, psychosocial

848
00:50:31.028 --> 00:50:33.668
factors, or clinical disease information.

849
00:50:34.178 --> 00:50:38.058
And then you can also link that information even further to biobank and

850
00:50:38.108 --> 00:50:41.868
repositories which house those genetic or omics

851
00:50:41.908 --> 00:50:45.738
markers. And the purpose of linking these data sets

852
00:50:45.828 --> 00:50:49.608
together is to create these multilevel data sets where you can begin to

853
00:50:49.668 --> 00:50:52.368
investigate variables at each of these levels

854
00:50:52.408 --> 00:50:56.168
individually and collectively to see how they impact

855
00:50:56.588 --> 00:51:00.368
cancer outcomes, all under a chronic stress hypothesis

856
00:51:00.728 --> 00:51:04.388
that states that we want to understand how factors outside the body

857
00:51:04.588 --> 00:51:08.288
get in under the skin, impact biology, and ultimately

858
00:51:08.568 --> 00:51:09.548
cancer outcomes.

859
00:51:10.468 --> 00:51:14.308
So just like at the biologic level, where

860
00:51:14.388 --> 00:51:18.268
you run assays and you identify molecular markers associated

861
00:51:18.308 --> 00:51:19.038
with disease,

862
00:51:19.868 --> 00:51:23.008
omics markers, proteomics markers, genetic markers,

863
00:51:23.988 --> 00:51:27.608
and then apply high-dimensional computing approaches like machine

864
00:51:27.668 --> 00:51:31.148
learning to identify which markers are associated with treatment

865
00:51:31.248 --> 00:51:35.088
response, for example. You can apply the same methodologies

866
00:51:35.408 --> 00:51:38.718
to the macro level, to the area level data as

867
00:51:38.768 --> 00:51:42.438
well. So it's through these data linkages and then these

868
00:51:42.488 --> 00:51:45.108
common data analysis applying

869
00:51:46.208 --> 00:51:50.108
methods from basic science to social data sets where you

