00:51:53.788 --> 00:51:55.468
pathways involved in cancer.

872
00:51:58.328 --> 00:52:01.648
So how do you go about doing those data linkages?

873
00:52:01.788 --> 00:52:03.808
So I'm going to start there. We've alluded to this.

874
00:52:03.928 --> 00:52:07.728
So you start doing the data linkages through a process called

875
00:52:07.828 --> 00:52:11.688
geocoding. So for geocoding, what you need there is you have a

876
00:52:11.768 --> 00:52:15.588
patient. Each patient is their own unique ID in the

877
00:52:15.628 --> 00:52:16.788
context of data.

878
00:52:17.748 --> 00:52:21.448
Each patient has their own bio samples that they are linked through

879
00:52:21.908 --> 00:52:25.168
to their own bio sample ID. If you have the

880
00:52:25.268 --> 00:52:28.768
address of a patient, you can take that point

881
00:52:28.928 --> 00:52:31.988
address, run it through statistical software like

882
00:52:32.028 --> 00:52:35.868
ArcGIS to generate a geocode aggregated

883
00:52:35.888 --> 00:52:39.808
up to the neighborhood in which that particular person lives at

884
00:52:39.848 --> 00:52:41.728
a census tract level, for example.

885
00:52:42.308 --> 00:52:45.888
So typically, that would generate a geocode that, again, is based on these

886
00:52:45.928 --> 00:52:49.588
administrative boundaries. So the first two digits often

887
00:52:49.628 --> 00:52:53.348
represent the state, the next three digits the county, and the

888
00:52:53.408 --> 00:52:56.728
following digits represent the census tract or census block group.

889
00:52:57.768 --> 00:53:00.288
So once you have that GEO ID,

890
00:53:01.168 --> 00:53:04.798
you're able to place each participant in the

891
00:53:04.848 --> 00:53:07.808
neighborhood they live in, and then the subsequent neighborhood

892
00:53:07.868 --> 00:53:11.588
exposures that person's exposed to at the

893
00:53:11.628 --> 00:53:15.448
neighborhood level. So you're essentially able to get an exposure profile

894
00:53:15.848 --> 00:53:18.788
for each of the patients and the bio samples.

895
00:53:18.968 --> 00:53:22.688
So you're able to use publicly available data to get exposure

896
00:53:22.728 --> 00:53:24.588
profiles for these types of studies.

897
00:53:26.678 --> 00:53:30.588
So just to give you an example of a study that integrates all of these

898
00:53:30.628 --> 00:53:34.528
levels together. In pancreatic cancer, we've conducted some

899
00:53:34.588 --> 00:53:38.568
studies that show that telomere length is associated with pancreatic cancer

